Fixes #2134

There is an inconsistency of behavior between functions in a `good and `bad` examples:

```javascript
// bad
[1, 2, 3].map(number => {
  const nextNumber = number + 1;
  `A string containing the ${nextNumber}.`;
});

// good
[1, 2, 3].map(number => `A string containing the ${number}.`);
```

Actually, the first one will generate an array of 3 `undefined` since we're not returning anything from the `map`-function.

Assuming that `good` and `bad` examples, which are compared side-by-side should only consist of code-style differences, not different logic, which in this case might cause losing the focus from the main point - code style.
